WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.520 --> 00:00:03.649
&gt;&gt;Announcer on video: In order to identify
and empower such individuals, I

00:00:03.649 --> 00:00:07.169
am proud to announce that my Aunt Doris Buffett
is

00:00:07.169 --> 00:00:11.290
committing $10 million to endow Learning by
Giving, a

00:00:11.290 --> 00:00:13.959
foundation that will be central to the development
of

00:00:13.959 --> 00:00:18.180
the social value investment model by fueling
a pipeline

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:21.060
of young leaders who will identify and fund
the most

00:00:21.060 --> 00:00:24.910
impactful projects across America. The premise
is

00:00:24.910 --> 00:00:28.320
simple: The foundation partners with universities
to

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:31.880
create courses in philanthropy and nonprofit
studies.

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:36.390
Each class at each school is then given a
$10,000 grant

00:00:36.390 --> 00:00:39.750
and students collaborate to identify the best
allocation

00:00:39.750 --> 00:00:43.220
for those funds in their local communities.
The

00:00:43.220 --> 00:00:45.260
students prepare reports on what they've done
and share

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:49.800
them on LearningByGivingFoundation.org, an
online

00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:52.610
resource where coursework is made available
to everyone on

00:00:52.610 --> 00:00:56.340
the planet. The web site was built using Google
tools

00:00:56.340 --> 00:00:59.040
and resources, and with the generous support
of Google's director

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:02.570
of university relations and many of their
employees.

00:01:02.570 --> 00:01:06.591
LivingByGivingFoundation.org is going live
today, and I

00:01:06.591 --> 00:01:10.684
encourage every one of you to use it and to
share it. [voice fades]

00:01:10.684 --> 00:01:14.170
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: And we welcome &gt;&gt;DORIS Buffett
with us today.

00:01:14.170 --> 00:01:16.340
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Thank you.
[Clapping]

00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:20.829
&gt;&gt;DORIS: I'm very happy to be here. This is
been quite an experience you know.

00:01:20.829 --> 00:01:24.090
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Well, we hope you've enjoyed it.
For those of you that don't know me, I'm Jennifer

00:01:24.090 --> 00:01:26.579
Barth,
and I work here, recently in the engineering

00:01:26.579 --> 00:01:29.840
office and
now in the office of the executive chairman.

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:32.030
So that
keeps me little busy on the side.

00:01:32.030 --> 00:01:33.719
&gt;&gt;DORIS: It would.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: But this is way more fun today,

00:01:33.719 --> 00:01:35.030
I
want you to know. [giggles]

00:01:35.030 --> 00:01:38.130
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Good.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: So I have to say, in looking at

00:01:38.130 --> 00:01:40.450
all
of my research, you've led a pretty interesting

00:01:40.450 --> 00:01:42.819
life.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Yes. I think so. It's had its ups

00:01:42.819 --> 00:01:46.359
and downs and I'm a late bloomer, but I'm
having a lot of fun

00:01:46.359 --> 00:01:48.140
now.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Hey, that's right. That's right.

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:49.859
I mean, your father was a Congressman?
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Yes.

00:01:49.859 --> 00:01:51.679
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Your brother's a little famous.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Yes.

00:01:51.679 --> 00:01:59.299
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Just a little. You've obviously
had some relationship -- tumultuous relationship

00:01:59.299 --> 00:02:01.429
history
with your mother that you talk about a lot

00:02:01.429 --> 00:02:03.859
in your book.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Oh, yes. That's true.

00:02:03.859 --> 00:02:05.070
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Millionairess.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Yes.

00:02:05.070 --> 00:02:07.350
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Not once, but twice.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Right.

00:02:07.350 --> 00:02:09.611
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: So --
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Lost it all the first time.

00:02:09.611 --> 00:02:15.130
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Yes. And to bad luck; not to
anything that you cover done differently?

00:02:15.130 --> 00:02:19.000
&gt;&gt;DORIS: No. Considering all the circumstances
it probably was inevitable.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.330
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: So I think it's interesting you
didn't necessarily want to tell the whole

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:29.350
story in your
book, Giving It All Away. Not initially.

00:02:29.350 --> 00:02:34.770
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Well, no. It's painful, but in order
to get the whole picture, you have to know

00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:37.440
the whole
story. So we went ahead and did it, and as

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:39.250
my brother
said, it's a very honest book.

00:02:39.250 --> 00:02:41.600
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Mm hmm.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: So if nothing else, it's an honest

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:44.080
book.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: So what changed your mind?

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:47.340
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Well, my brother did. We were on
a

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:49.040
plane and she said, "Doris, you've got a write
a book

00:02:49.040 --> 00:02:50.650
about what you're doing." I said, "Oh, for
heaven's

00:02:50.650 --> 00:02:52.370
sakes. I don't know anything about that."
He said,

00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:53.900
"Well, you've really got to." I said, "Well,
it's

00:02:53.900 --> 00:02:56.090
all -- it's all anecdotal." He said, "That's
what

00:02:56.090 --> 00:02:58.180
people love." I said, "Well, I don't know
how to

00:02:58.180 --> 00:03:00.480
write." He said, "I'll get you a ghost writer."
So

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:03.001
he's rather persuasive and I actually went
back to my

00:03:03.001 --> 00:03:04.380
seat and I thought, well, I've got the title,
and that

00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:09.510
would be Here's the Deal because everything
we do is

00:03:09.510 --> 00:03:12.740
'here's the deal'. It involves collaboration.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Mm hmm.

00:03:12.740 --> 00:03:16.200
&gt;&gt;DORIS: So they voted that out so that was
too

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:17.200
bad.
[Laughing]

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:20.330
&gt;&gt;DORIS: And then Bono actually advised me
to

00:03:20.330 --> 00:03:22.170
do it. How about that.
[Laughing]

00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:26.120
&gt;&gt;DORIS: So that was very persuasive.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: I bet so.

00:03:26.120 --> 00:03:28.950
[Laughing]
&gt;&gt;DORIS: So that's how it came to be, and

00:03:28.950 --> 00:03:31.460
I
knew a fellow in Fredericksburg, who was a

00:03:31.460 --> 00:03:35.540
wonderful
writer and worked for the Freelance Star,

00:03:35.540 --> 00:03:38.040
and he was
eager to do it. So we just got together and

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:42.120
I just went
on, and on, and on, and he was game to take

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:44.800
it it all
down and I was very happy with the result.

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:52.210
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: It's fascinating. I am curious
because you've come from so many different

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:54.480
highs and
lows. How did you know you could do this?

00:03:54.480 --> 00:03:56.960
I mean,
you've been -- I'm the mom of a four-year-old,

00:03:56.960 --> 00:04:00.330
full-time
career at times, you know, you struggle. I

00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:02.890
was an actor
at one time so I know some way of feast or

00:04:02.890 --> 00:04:03.890
famine.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Yeah.

00:04:03.890 --> 00:04:09.069
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: How'd you know you could do this?
I mean, you've got philanthropy and organizations

00:04:09.069 --> 00:04:12.980
touching lives on a one-to-one basis.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Well, that's what we try to do. First

00:04:12.980 --> 00:04:15.390
of
all, that was my aim. I wasn't going to go

00:04:15.390 --> 00:04:21.049
into more
esoteric things. I wanted -- I had the money

00:04:21.049 --> 00:04:24.240
and I was
very lucky to have that, and it fit into who

00:04:24.240 --> 00:04:29.190
I am. I'm
not a saint, I'm not saying that, but I have

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:31.800
always
been aware of other people's needs and wished

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:35.151
to help
them, and now I can just go full gun. I was

00:04:35.151 --> 00:04:37.569
-- it was
wonderful. I was all ready to go. I already

00:04:37.569 --> 00:04:40.870
had a
501(3) when my mother died, so I was out of

00:04:40.870 --> 00:04:41.870
the starting
gate.

00:04:41.870 --> 00:04:44.590
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Mm hmm.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: I made a few mistakes in the beginning,

00:04:44.590 --> 00:04:46.689
but
not many, because I had a wonderful group

00:04:46.689 --> 00:04:50.729
of people were
working with me who were very bright, and

00:04:50.729 --> 00:04:53.210
that was our
aim and has remained our aim, and we just

00:04:53.210 --> 00:04:56.370
keep on doing
it as long as the money holds out.

00:04:56.370 --> 00:04:58.879
[Laughing]
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Eventually the last check will bounce

00:04:58.879 --> 00:05:01.069
and then I'm out of business.
[Laughing]

00:05:01.069 --> 00:05:05.639
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Let's hope not. I'm curious. Can
you recall that first instance where you wrote

00:05:05.639 --> 00:05:09.330
that
first really large check or you got that first

00:05:09.330 --> 00:05:11.990
letter
back from someone that you made a difference

00:05:11.990 --> 00:05:13.389
in their
lives? Can you recount something like that?

00:05:13.389 --> 00:05:19.870
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Well, I know that -- I know the very
first thing we did was to offer scholarships

00:05:19.870 --> 00:05:22.870
for
women -- and that's after everybody else had

00:05:22.870 --> 00:05:26.009
turned them
down -- so we took the losers -- and all of

00:05:26.009 --> 00:05:28.370
them
graduated, just one didn't. So that was very

00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:32.090
successful
because I had a marvelous young woman who

00:05:32.090 --> 00:05:35.360
said she never
wanted any children and now she had 135.

00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:38.120
[Laughing]
&gt;&gt;DORIS: And she rose to the occasion, and

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:40.740
she's a mother hen so that worked really well.
And then

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:45.629
the next thing was to educate battered women
-- formerly

00:05:45.629 --> 00:05:47.240
battered women. So that's worked out fairly
-- when you

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:49.719
change a life like that, it's really dramatic.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Sure.

00:05:49.719 --> 00:05:54.401
&gt;&gt;DORIS: So then I thought up this, the
Learning by Giving --

00:05:54.401 --> 00:05:55.860
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: That's right.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: -- and thought why am I doing this

00:05:55.860 --> 00:05:58.539
all
by myself? [chuckles] So here we have a whole

00:05:58.539 --> 00:06:04.430
generation of
extremely bright and energetic people and

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:07.659
they're
idealistic, and they're hard working, so why

00:06:07.659 --> 00:06:11.699
not get
them in on the game. So that's how we first

00:06:11.699 --> 00:06:14.569
started with
this, which has become a really big deal across

00:06:14.569 --> 00:06:18.169
the
country. I'm so old that I remember when Communists

00:06:18.169 --> 00:06:21.409
were a big threat, and I remember that they
used to go

00:06:21.409 --> 00:06:26.319
to universities and colleges and pick off
the 5 percent

00:06:26.319 --> 00:06:30.279
that were the most compassionate and the brightest
and

00:06:30.279 --> 00:06:34.839
recruit them. So I thought, well, it worked
for them,

00:06:34.839 --> 00:06:37.219
you know, so I think I'll try that, too. So
that's what

00:06:37.219 --> 00:06:38.849
we try to do.
[Laughing]

00:06:38.849 --> 00:06:41.770
&gt;&gt;DORIS: And it has worked. It is working
as

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:43.591
we speak.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Right. So it appears that your

00:06:43.591 --> 00:06:48.919
brother and Bono were right.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Well, I'd like to think so.

00:06:48.919 --> 00:06:51.389
[Laughing]
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: I want to know, you mentioned

00:06:51.389 --> 00:06:54.809
one
time about growing up in the childhood you

00:06:54.809 --> 00:06:58.789
had, and the
education you learned through life experience

00:06:58.789 --> 00:07:01.770
about a
fairy god mother. What's your idea of a fairy

00:07:01.770 --> 00:07:02.770
god
mother?

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:04.330
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Me [chuckles] now.
[Laughing]

00:07:04.330 --> 00:07:09.201
&gt;&gt;DORIS: No. I always wished -- I was in a
very difficult situation and I always wished

00:07:09.201 --> 00:07:12.119
there was a
fairy god mother would come along and just

00:07:12.119 --> 00:07:16.219
kidnap me, or
take me away, or straighten it out or show

00:07:16.219 --> 00:07:18.719
me some
sympathy, whatever it was, but that never

00:07:18.719 --> 00:07:22.669
happened so
then I'm now becoming my own. And I'm making

00:07:22.669 --> 00:07:26.630
myself
happy doing this, and then thousands of people.

00:07:26.630 --> 00:07:29.719
Literally thousands of people and I don't
want to sound

00:07:29.719 --> 00:07:32.059
braggadocio, but it has changed their lives.
Their

00:07:32.059 --> 00:07:35.210
letters are magnificent. I have a whole stack,
and that

00:07:35.210 --> 00:07:38.339
represents 1/100ths, probably. But these are
the most

00:07:38.339 --> 00:07:40.699
touched by it and their lives are really changed
and

00:07:40.699 --> 00:07:42.900
they're so grateful, and their children are
doing well

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:46.219
by it. Everybody's doing well by it.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Do you think if you hadn't had

00:07:46.219 --> 00:07:50.710
your
own misfortune that you would feel to this

00:07:50.710 --> 00:07:52.699
extent to do
what you do?

00:07:52.699 --> 00:07:56.810
&gt;&gt;DORIS: I think I'm a little weird. I don't
think probably -- you know, what I look at

00:07:56.810 --> 00:07:59.889
my
generation, I don't think so. I mean, I do

00:07:59.889 --> 00:08:02.659
know --
well, I shouldn't be so hard on myself. I

00:08:02.659 --> 00:08:06.509
always find
people who I felt needed some help and tried

00:08:06.509 --> 00:08:11.379
to do, you
know, in my own little teenybopper way, something

00:08:11.379 --> 00:08:14.562
to
help out. But what can you do? I mean, I was

00:08:14.562 --> 00:08:17.839
bound by
the family rules. To begin with, I was living

00:08:17.839 --> 00:08:19.199
under
their roof, and "When you're living under

00:08:19.199 --> 00:08:21.159
this roof you
will obey the rules," that kind of thing.

00:08:21.159 --> 00:08:23.009
And so I
didn't have a lot, and I didn't have any money

00:08:23.009 --> 00:08:25.039
except
what I made babysitting.

00:08:25.039 --> 00:08:27.210
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Mm hmm.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: You --

00:08:27.210 --> 00:08:29.449
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: You've come a long way.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: What's so funny about that?

00:08:29.449 --> 00:08:34.060
[Laughing]
&gt;&gt;DORIS: So yeah. But I was always aware.

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:36.270
I
always was aware. When I was in high school

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:38.710
I did have
one of those 'Save the Children' kids from

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:41.770
World War II,
and I don't know of anybody else that did

00:08:41.770 --> 00:08:46.140
that. So
yeah. It was there. It was in place and all

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:47.480
it needed
was some money.

00:08:47.480 --> 00:08:50.740
[Laughing]
&gt;&gt;DORIS: And maybe some wisdom. Yeah.

00:08:50.740 --> 00:08:56.540
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Well, you had the Sunshine Lady
Foundation, which has helped countless women,

00:08:56.540 --> 00:09:00.810
as you've
said; and then also you've helped those in

00:09:00.810 --> 00:09:03.190
prison to get
educated and turn themselves around.

00:09:03.190 --> 00:09:06.450
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Mm hmm
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Tell me about the transition from

00:09:06.450 --> 00:09:09.200
the Sunshine Lady Foundation to the Learning
by Giving

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:13.650
foundation.
&gt;&gt;DORIS: Well, we used to have something called

00:09:13.650 --> 00:09:17.810
Sunbeams, and they were people aged 8 to 80
who would

00:09:17.810 --> 00:09:20.950
help me get rid of the money in a meaningful
way. I

00:09:20.950 --> 00:09:24.670
don't mean to stand on the corner or anything.
And we

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:28.690
had a couple of them who were students actually,
and

00:09:28.690 --> 00:09:32.200
they were over at Davidson College in western
North

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:34.810
Carolina, and they were just so busy thinking
up things

00:09:34.810 --> 00:09:38.990
to spend money on around there to make things
better over there and

00:09:38.990 --> 00:09:42.320
after -- I'm not -- I can't exactly remember
this, but I

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:45.480
do know my grandson, Alexander and I, stopped
at

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:50.330
Davidson coming home from Omaha, and they
put on sort of

00:09:50.330 --> 00:09:53.960
a presentation to show me what they were doing,
and it

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:57.900
was so good that both the professor and the
two of us

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:02.340
thought it might be -- turn it into a course.
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Mm hmm.

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:05.090
&gt;&gt;DORIS: So he was the first one, and from
then

00:10:05.090 --> 00:10:09.180
on it has spread. There's one in my hometown
now,

00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:12.840
Fredericksburg, Virginia, and the professor
there

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:15.430
mirrors every other professor that's involved
with this.

00:10:15.430 --> 00:10:19.330
They love the course because they get engaged
students,

00:10:19.330 --> 00:10:21.140
you know, you're not fighting somebody typing
all the

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:24.840
time or whatever it is they have to put up
with. They

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:27.530
just adore it. It's always oversubscribed
in every

00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:32.340
school where we've presented it, and the kids
get pretty

00:10:32.340 --> 00:10:34.880
emotional about the one -- you know, they
go out and

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:36.450
look at local --
&gt;&gt;JENNIFER: Mm hmm.

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:37.930
&gt;&gt;DORIS: -- we don't go sending it off to
Bangkok

00:10:37.930 --> 00:10:40.890
because we want them to really feel and way
the know you

00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:46.380
do it. And so they go out in teams and they
decide

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:49.740
which ones they've interviewed looked the
best to them,

00:10:49.740 --> 00:10:52.520
and then that director comes in and speaks
to the class.

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:55.620
There may be four more steps, I don't know,
but I do

00:10:55.620 --> 00:10:59.340
know they end up arguing, and that's what
they like the

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:01.750
best. They really -- they pick their favorites,
and boy

00:11:01.750 --> 00:11:06.640
do they stand up for them. So that's a good
exercise.

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:09.050
We don't tell them where to spend the money.
They can

00:11:09.050 --> 00:11:11.640
divide it up ten different ways or give it
all to

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:13.020
one place, but they've never been able to
do that.

00:11:13.020 --> 00:11:16.860
They can't agree on that. So it has benefit.
And as I

00:11:16.860 --> 00:11:19.160
said, I don't have anything to say about where
it goes

00:11:19.160 --> 00:11:21.420
except it has to be local because that's how
you learn

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:24.030
what your community's like and when you're
high above

00:11:24.030 --> 00:11:27.420
Cuyahoga's waters, you may not know what's
going on

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:28.420
below.
[Laughing]

00:11:28.420 --> 00:11:35.780
&gt;&gt;DORIS: So it's been very exciting because
we're creating a whole army of knowledgeable,

00:11:35.780 --> 00:11:39.610
bright,
energetic kids. Pardon if I shouldn't say

00:11:39.610 --> 00:11:43.460
kids. Young
people? That makes me old people. I don't

